## Import

> **Bulk import tip:** [`tools/generate_import/generate_import.py`](https://github.com/pescobar/terraform-provider-slurm/blob/master/tools/generate_import/generate_import.py)
> queries a running `slurmrestd` instance and generates ready-to-use HCL files plus
> `import {}` blocks for all QOS, accounts, and users in one shot. See its
> [README](https://github.com/pescobar/terraform-provider-slurm/blob/master/tools/generate_import/README.md)
> for usage.

Import an account by its Slurm name:

```bash
tofu import slurm_account.physics physics
```

### Null-preservation after import

Every attribute on `slurm_account` besides `id` and `name` is **Optional-only**
(no `Computed`). The provider only writes such a field into state when it is
already non-null in prior state. This prevents Slurm's inherited defaults —
such as `fairshare = 1` or a QOS list inherited from the parent account — from
appearing as drift after a fresh import.

After `tofu import`, every Optional field (`fairshare`, `default_qos`,
`allowed_qos`, `parent_account`, etc.) will be null in state, since import only
populates `id` and `name` before the first refresh. A **reconcile apply** is
needed to write config-declared values to Slurm and populate state for any
field your configuration sets — if your configuration leaves a field unset
(matching the null state left by import), there is nothing to reconcile for
that field and `tofu plan` will already be clean without it.

### Standard import workflow

```bash
# Step 1 — import (Optional fields are null in state)
tofu import slurm_account.physics physics

# Step 2 — reconcile apply (writes config-declared values to Slurm)
tofu apply

# Step 3 — verify clean plan (must report no changes)
tofu plan -detailed-exitcode
```

### `parent_account` drift is not detected once set

`parent_account` has a stricter null-preservation rule than the other Optional
fields: it is only written into state when Slurm's API returns a *non-empty*
parent (in addition to prior state already being non-null). Slurm reports an
account directly under the built-in `root` account as an **empty** parent —
which is indistinguishable, from the provider's point of view, from "not
tracked yet". Consequence: once you've reconciled a non-root `parent_account`,
an out-of-band change that moves the account back under `root` (or a failed
apply that silently leaves it there) is **not detected as drift** — `tofu plan`
will keep reporting no changes even though Slurm no longer matches your
configuration. Verified against a live cluster. There is currently no
workaround short of periodically checking `sacctmgr show account` directly.
